            "content": "# Syscall Fast-Path Acceleration\n\n## Architecture Overview\n\nkbox intercepts guest syscalls and routes them to an in-process Linux kernel\n(LKL).  Three interception tiers trade isolation for speed:\n\n| Tier | Mechanism | Latency | When used |\n|------|-----------|---------|-----------|\n| 3 | seccomp USER_NOTIF | ~13-28us | Shell commands, --net, --syscall-mode=seccomp |\n| 1 | SIGSYS trap (RET_TRAP) | ~16-24us | Trap fallback when rewrite infeasible |\n| 2 | Binary rewriting | ~1-19us | Non-shell direct binaries (AUTO default) |\n\nAUTO mode selects the fastest available tier per command:\n- Shell commands (sh, bash, ash, etc.) → seccomp (fork/exec coherence)\n- Commands with --net → seccomp (SLIRP requires supervisor poll loop)\n- Non-shell, non-net binaries → rewrite (with trap and seccomp fallbacks)\n\n## Dispatch Pipeline\n\n```\nGuest syscall instruction\n    │\n    ├── [rewrite] SVC/syscall patched to B/JMP → trampoline\n    │       │\n    │       ├── local fast-path (kbox_dispatch_try_local_fast_path)\n    │       │     ├── Tier 1: pure emulation (getpid=1, getppid=0, gettid=1)\n    │       │     └── Tier 2: always-CONTINUE (50 syscalls → host kernel)\n    │       │\n    │       └── service thread (futex IPC → kbox_dispatch_request → LKL)\n    │\n    ├── [trap] BPF returns RET_TRAP → SIGSYS handler\n    │       │\n    │       ├── local fast-path (same as above)\n    │       └── service thread (same as above)\n    │\n    └── [seccomp] BPF returns USER_NOTIF → supervisor process\n            └── kbox_dispatch_request → LKL → ioctl response\n```\n\n## Changes (vs commit 47157b2)\n\n12 files changed, 371 insertions, 169 deletions.\n\n### 1. Direct guest memory access with fault recovery (procmem.c)\n\n**Problem**: In trap/rewrite mode (same address space), `kbox_current_read`,\n`kbox_current_write`, and `kbox_current_read_string` used\n`pread(/proc/self/mem)` and `process_vm_writev`.  The BPF filter's IP gate\nblocked these syscalls with EPERM (kbox text segment IPs not in registered\ntrampoline ranges), causing stat to SKIP in rewrite mode on aarch64.\n\n**Fix**: Replace with direct `memcpy` wrapped in `sigsetjmp`/`siglongjmp`\nfault recovery.  A scoped SIGSEGV/SIGBUS handler is installed and restored\naround each access so that guest `rt_sigaction(SIGSEGV, ...)` calls\n(which CONTINUE to the host kernel) are not clobbered.\n\n- `safe_memcpy()`: sigsetjmp + memcpy + sigaction save/restore per call\n- `kbox_current_read_string()`: byte-by-byte copy under fault protection\n  with `INT_MAX` length clamp\n- Unmapped guest pointers return `-EFAULT` instead of crashing\n\n### 2. Guest-thread local fast-path (seccomp-dispatch.c)\n\n**Problem**: All trap/rewrite dispatches went through the service thread via\nfutex IPC, even for syscalls that never touch LKL.\n\n**Fix**: New `kbox_dispatch_try_local_fast_path()` called before the service\nthread handoff in both `direct_trap_execute` and `rewrite_dispatch_request`.\n\nTier 1 -- pure emulation (zero overhead):\n- `getpid` → 1, `getppid` → 0, `gettid` → 1\n\nTier 2 -- always-CONTINUE (host kernel handles directly, no IPC):\n- brk, futex, rseq, set_tid_address, set_robust_list\n- munmap, mremap, membarrier, madvise\n- wait4, waitid, exit, exit_group\n- rt_sigreturn, rt_sigaltstack, setitimer, getitimer\n- setpgid, getpgid, getsid, setsid, fork, vfork\n- sched_yield, sched_setparam, sched_getparam, sched_setscheduler,\n  sched_getscheduler, sched_get_priority_max, sched_get_priority_min,\n  sched_setaffinity, sched_getaffinity\n- getrlimit, getrusage\n- epoll_create1, epoll_ctl, epoll_wait, epoll_pwait\n- ppoll, pselect6, poll\n- nanosleep, clock_nanosleep\n- timerfd_create, timerfd_settime, timerfd_gettime\n- eventfd, eventfd2\n- statfs, fstatfs, sysinfo\n\nAll 50 entries verified unconditional in `kbox_dispatch_request`.\n\nThe dead `kbox_dispatch_try_rewrite_wrapper_fast_path` (which called LKL on\nthe guest thread, causing races and crashes) was deleted.\n\n### 3. Removed unsafe guest-thread LKL dispatch (rewrite.c)\n\n**Problem**: `rewrite_dispatch_request` called\n`kbox_dispatch_try_rewrite_wrapper_fast_path` which invoked `forward_newfstatat`,\n`forward_openat`, etc. directly on the guest thread.  LKL requires its own\nthread context; calling it from the guest thread raced with the service thread\nand crashed under sustained load on aarch64.\n\n**Fix**: Removed the wrapper fast-path entirely.  All LKL-touching dispatches\ngo through the service thread.  The fallback to `kbox_dispatch_request` on the\nguest thread was also removed; service thread failure is a hard error.\n\n### 4. Spin-then-futex IPC optimization (syscall-trap.c)\n\n**Problem**: Each intercepted syscall required 2-4 futex syscalls and 2\nscheduler wakeups for the guest ↔ service thread handoff.\n\n**Fix**: Both `wait_for_pending_dispatch` (guest side) and\n`trap_service_thread_main` (service side) now spin for 1024 iterations with\narchitecture-appropriate hints (`pause` on x86_64, `yield` on aarch64) before\nfalling back to `futex(FUTEX_WAIT_PRIVATE)`.  This catches fast LKL cache hits\n(~1.5-3us) without kernel round-trips.\n\n### 5. SQPOLL mode (syscall-trap.c, cli.c, image.c)\n\n**New**: `--sqpoll` flag makes the service thread busy-poll `has_pending_request`\nwithout ever falling back to futex.  Eliminates all scheduling latency at the\ncost of dedicating one CPU core.  Available for latency-sensitive workloads and\nbenchmarking.\n\n### 6. AUTO mode enabled (image.c)\n\n**Problem**: `KBOX_AUTO_ENABLE_USERSPACE_FAST_PATH` was hardcoded to 0,\npinning AUTO to seccomp.  All trap/rewrite optimizations were unreachable in\nthe default mode.\n\n**Fix**: Flipped to 1.  AUTO now selects rewrite/trap for non-shell, non-net\ncommands.  The aarch64 cancel-wrapper override was removed (all LKL dispatches\nnow go through the service thread safely).\n\nSelection rules:\n- `is_shell_command()` → seccomp (fork coherence)\n- `args->net` → seccomp (SLIRP requires supervisor poll loop)\n- Binary with fork/clone sites → seccomp\n- Otherwise → rewrite (fallback: trap → seccomp)\n\n## Benchmarks\n\nRelease build, 10K iterations, 3-run average, us/call.\n\n### node1 (x86_64, AMD Threadripper 2990WX)\n\n| Syscall | Baseline seccomp | Patched AUTO | Speedup |\n|---------|---------|---------|---------|\n| stat | 13.8 | 16.9 | 0.82x |\n| open+close | 26.3 | 23.1 | 1.14x |\n| lseek+read | 2.1 | 1.9 | 1.11x |\n| write | 1.4 | 1.4 | 1.00x |\n| getpid | <0.1 | <0.1 | -- |\n\nx86_64 stat is slower in AUTO because the per-call `sigsetjmp` + `sigaction`\nsave/restore in `safe_memcpy` costs ~3us, exceeding the seccomp USER_NOTIF\nround-trip savings.  open+close and lseek+read are faster because the local\nfast-path bypasses the service thread for the surrounding brk/mmap/munmap\ncalls.\n\n### arm (aarch64, Marvell ThunderX2)\n\n| Syscall | Baseline seccomp | Patched AUTO | Speedup |\n|---------|---------|---------|---------|\n| stat | 22.5 | 18.2 | 1.24x |\n| open+close | 42.6 | 30.7 | 1.39x |\n| lseek+read | 1.3 | 1.4 | 0.93x |\n| write | 1.4 | 1.4 | 1.00x |\n| getpid | <0.1 | <0.1 | -- |\n\naarch64 shows clear wins across the board.  stat is 1.24x faster (rewrite\navoids USER_NOTIF + LKL inode cache is warm).  open+close is 1.39x faster\n(trap/rewrite avoids the cross-process ioctl pair).\n\n### Explicit mode comparison (node1, patched)\n\n| Syscall | Seccomp | Trap | Rewrite |\n|---------|---------|------|---------|\n| stat | 13.2 | 17.6 | 16.7 |\n| open+close | 26.0 | 20.3 | 19.0 |\n| lseek+read | 2.2 | 1.7 | 1.5 |\n| write | 1.4 | 1.4 | 1.4 |\n| getpid | <0.1 | <0.1 | <0.1 |\n\n### Explicit mode comparison (arm, patched)\n\n| Syscall | Seccomp | Trap | Rewrite |\n|---------|---------|------|---------|\n| stat | 22.3 | 24.0 | 18.5 |\n| open+close | 42.1 | 31.0 | 30.5 |\n| lseek+read | 1.3 | 1.4 | 1.4 |\n| write | 1.4 | 1.4 | 1.4 |\n| getpid | <0.1 | <0.1 | <0.1 |\n\n## Validation\n\n| Test | node1 (x86_64) | arm (aarch64) |\n|------|----------------|---------------|\n| Unit tests (ASAN/UBSAN) | 240/240 | 240/240 |\n| Integration (AUTO mode) | 47/47 | 47/47 |\n| seccomp direct binary | 3/3 | 3/3 |\n| trap direct binary | 3/3 | 3/3 |\n| rewrite direct binary | 3/3 | 3/3 |\n| trap 50K stress | PASS | PASS |\n| rewrite 50K stress | PASS | PASS |\n\n## Reviewed By\n\nEach round of changes was reviewed by Gemini and Codex in parallel.\n\nFindings addressed:\n- Guest `rt_sigaction(SIGSEGV)` overwrites fault handler → scoped save/restore\n- Rewrite fallback still called LKL on guest thread → hard error\n- `isb` is a pipeline flush, not a spin hint → replaced with `yield`\n- `(int)len` truncates at INT_MAX → clamped\n- CONTINUE list correctness → all 50 entries verified unconditional\n- `goto dispatch` label → verified correct\n- Acquire/release memory ordering → consistent across spin/futex\n\n## Future Work\n\n### Binary Translation Cache (BTC) for x86_64\n\nBare 2-byte `syscall` (0F 05) on x86_64 cannot be patched in place (5-byte\n`jmp rel32` needed).  The paper \"Architectural Paradigms for Accelerating\nSystem Call Interception in Library Operating Systems\" proposes relocating\nthe containing basic block to a Binary Translation Cache:\n\n1. Walk instruction boundaries around the bare `0F 05`\n2. Relocate the block to a BTC region (PROT_EXEC, within ±2GB)\n3. In the BTC, replace `syscall` with the trampoline call\n4. Patch the original site with `jmp rel32` + NOPs\n5. Handle RIP-relative addressing fixups in relocated instructions\n\nThis eliminates the SIGSYS fallback for bare syscall sites.  Estimated\n300+ line change to `rewrite.c` and `x86-decode.c`.\n\n### Synthetic vDSO for clock_gettime\n\n`clock_gettime` and `clock_getres` are pure host calls (no LKL).  Moving\nthem to the local fast-path as CONTINUE broke bench_test timing (the bench\nitself uses clock_gettime).  The correct approach: intercept at the\ntrampoline level and call the host vDSO function directly, bypassing the\ndispatch pipeline entirely.\n\n### Lockless SPSC ring buffer\n\nThe paper proposes replacing the atomic-flag + futex handoff with an\nio_uring-style SPSC ring buffer polled by a pinned LKL thread.  For\nsingle-threaded guests (the only kind trap/rewrite supports), queue depth\nis 1, so the data structure doesn't help.  The SQPOLL mode already provides\nthe busy-poll behavior.  This becomes valuable when multi-threaded guest\nsupport is added.\n\n### Syscall User Dispatch (SUD)\n\nLinux 5.11+ provides `prctl(PR_SET_SYSCALL_USER_DISPATCH)` with a userspace\nselector byte.  SUD delivers SIGSYS without the seccomp BPF evaluation,\nreducing signal delivery overhead.  Combined with binary rewriting, SUD\nwould catch JIT-generated and missed syscall sites that the rewriter\ncannot patch.\n\n### eBPF safe batching\n\nAllow the guest to submit verified eBPF bytecode representing chained\nsyscall sequences.  The LKL service thread executes the batch natively,\nreducing boundary crossings for tight I/O loops.  Very high complexity;\ndepends on an in-LKL eBPF verifier.\n",
