            "new_string": "### Syscall User Dispatch (SUD)\n\nLinux 5.11+ provides `prctl(PR_SET_SYSCALL_USER_DISPATCH)` with a userspace\nselector byte.  SUD delivers SIGSYS without the seccomp BPF evaluation,\nreducing signal delivery overhead.\n\n**Status: evaluated and rejected for the in-process model.**  SUD's API takes\none contiguous IP range where syscalls are ALLOWED; everything outside gets\nSIGSYS.  kbox needs the inverse: ALLOW kbox/LKL/libc code, BLOCK guest code.\nSince kbox, LKL, and libc are at different non-contiguous addresses in the\nshared process, no single range covers them all.  Setting the range to kbox's\ntext segment (`__executable_start` to `_etext`) blocks libc syscalls from the\nservice thread (futex, sigaction), crashing the sandbox.\n\nThe `kbox_install_sud()` and `kbox_install_seccomp_deny_only()` functions\nremain in `seccomp-bpf.c` as infrastructure for future use if either:\n- kbox switches to static linking (libc in kbox's text segment), or\n- SUD gains support for multiple allowed ranges, or\n- The guest is loaded at a known contiguous range that can be carved out.\n\n### io_uring IORING_OP_MSG_RING for IPC\n\nLinux 5.18+ provides `IORING_OP_MSG_RING` for direct ring-to-ring CQE\nposting.  This enables lockless, zero-syscall IPC between the guest and\nservice threads without futex scheduling overhead.  Both hosts have the\nrequired kernel versions.\n\nThe implementation would replace the spin-then-futex handoff:\n1. Guest thread submits syscall args as an SQE on its local ring\n2. `IORING_OP_MSG_RING` posts the request to the service thread's ring\n3. Service thread processes via LKL, posts result back via MSG_RING\n4. Guest thread reaps the CQE from its ring\n\nThis eliminates the futex fallback entirely while avoiding the CPU waste\nof SQPOLL mode.  The `COOP_TASKRUN` flag further reduces IPIs by deferring\ncompletions until the application polls.\n\n### Zepoline for x86_64 bare syscall sites\n\nThe zpoline technique replaces `syscall` (0F 05) with `call *%rax` (FF D0) --\nsame 2 bytes.  %rax holds the syscall number (a small integer near 0); the\ncall targets a NOP sled at page zero that slides into a trampoline.\n\nkbox already has `kbox_rewrite_probe_x86_64_page_zero()` which maps the NOP\nsled when `vm.mmap_min_addr=0`.  On stock kernels (mmap_min_addr=65536), this\nfails.  The BTC approach (basic block relocation with `jmp rel32`) is the\nstock-kernel alternative.  Zpoline remains the fastest option when page zero\nis available.\n\n### LKL SMP and sharded instances\n\nLKL enforces a single global lock for all kernel entries.  Under heavy\nconcurrent load, this serializes the network and filesystem stacks.\nTwo mitigation paths:\n- **SMP within LKL**: break the global lock into per-subsystem locks,\n  provision multiple vCPUs, implement emulated IPIs.  Deep kernel changes.\n- **Sharded LKL instances**: spawn multiple independent LKL instances,\n  route requests by FD range or socket hash.  Simpler but doesn't solve\n  shared-state issues (concurrent writes to the same inode).\n\n### eBPF safe batching (bpftime)\n\nAllow the guest to submit verified eBPF bytecode representing chained\nsyscall sequences.  The LKL service thread executes the batch natively,\nreducing boundary crossings for tight I/O loops.  bpftime provides a\nuserspace eBPF runtime with LLVM JIT/AOT, achieving 10x reduction in\nuprobe overhead vs kernel uprobes.  Very high complexity; depends on an\nin-LKL eBPF verifier or bpftime integration.",
