ng.\n\n**HIGH-2: `ctx.host_root = NULL` in launch paths** (`image.c:251`)\n\nBoth `run_trap_launch` and `run_rewrite_launch` set `ctx.host_root = NULL` via `init_launch_ctx`. The seccomp path sets `host_root` to the LKL mount point. With `host_root = NULL`, path translation in `translate_guest_path` will break -- `kbox_translate_path_for_lkl` needs a non-NULL `host_root` to resolve guest paths to LKL filesystem paths. Same issue as HIGH-1 from rev 2: the trap/rewrite paths don't initialize LKL.\n\nThis means the trap and rewrite launch paths can only work for syscalls that don't touch the virtual filesystem (i.e., CONTINUE-only workloads). This may be the intended scope for this PR, but it's a hard crash on the first `open(\"/etc/passwd\")` and needs either a guard or documentation.\n\n**MED-1: `active_rewrite_runtime` global without atomics** (`rewrite.c:57`)\n\nSame pattern as the `active_trap_runtime` issue. Written in main thread, read in rewrite dispatch (which is the inline call from guest code, same thread). Since rewrite mode runs in-process single-threaded, this is actually safe -- no signal handler race here. The write happens before the guest starts executing. Downgrade from prior review.\n\n**MED-2: `pread_full` now in three files** -- `elf.c`, `rewrite.c`, and potentially loader files.\n\n**MED-3: aarch64 trampoline slot is written while mapping is PROT_WRITE|PROT_EXEC** (`rewrite.c:1516-1521`)\n\nThe trampoline address is inside the guest's exec mapping (past the end of the segment's file-backed data but within `mem_size`). `make_exec_mappings_writable` adds PROT_WRITE to exec pages, the trampoline is written, then protections are restored. But between write and icache flush, there's a window where another thread could execute stale icache. Single-threaded, so not a practical issue.\n\n**LOW-1: Missing loader files in git** -- still not staged. Build will fail on clean checkout.\n\n**LOW-2: x86_64 page-zero trampoline requires `vm.mmap_min_addr = 0`** -- correctly probed and reported, but the rewrite path in AUTO mode (`image.c:780`) gates on `exec_probe.feasible`, so if `mmap_min_addr != 0` on x86_64, AUTO falls through to trap. Correct behavior.\n\n**LOW-3: `write_le64` defined in rewrite.c but not in elf.c** -- elf.c uses `set_le64` in tests and `read_le64` in code. Naming inconsistency between files.\n\n### What's new and clean\n\n- The x86_64 NOP-sled page-zero trampoline is an elegant solution: `call *%rax` with any syscall number in RAX lands somewhere in a 64KB NOP sled that slides to the entry stub. No per-site trampoline needed. One page, all sites covered.\n- The aarch64 per-slot trampoline design (B instruction -> 32-byte slot with LDR literal + BR) handles the 128MB branch range limitation correctly. Slots are placed just past the segment's mem_size, within the page-aligned mapping.\n- `kbox_rewrite_runtime_install` has proper cleanup: `writable` flag tracks whether exec pages need protection restoration, `goto out` handles all error paths, `runtime_site_array_reset` frees collected sites.\n- Origin map validation in dispatch (`kbox_rewrite_origin_map_contains`) prevents arbitrary code from reaching the dispatch function -- only patched sites are accepted.\n- icache flush via `__builtin___clear_cache` after patching and before protection restoration is correct for aarch64.\n- The AUTO cascade (rewrite -> trap -> seccomp) with clear verbose logging at each decision point is good for debuggability.\n- 47/47 integration tests still pass (seccomp path unaffected by all changes).\n\n### Verdict\n\nThe rewrite runtime is now complete end-to-end for the first time. The architecture is sound: patch syscall instructions -> trampoline -> C dispatch -> host syscall or LKL emulation -> return to guest. HIGH-2 (no LKL in trap/rewrite paths) is the practical blocker -- these paths work for CONTINUE-only syscalls but will crash on any LKL-routed syscall. LOW-1 (unstaged loader files) remains a build blocker for clean checkouts. The `sysenter` patching in HIGH-1 is a minor ABI concern worth documenting.",
