            "new_string": "## Performance Baseline (x86_64, 10K iterations, Alpine ext4)\n\nMeasured 2026-03-23, release build (`BUILD=release`), `tests/guest/bench-test`\non node1 (x86-64). Median of 5 runs each. Native = bare metal (no kbox).\nDefault mode is `--syscall-mode=auto` which falls back to seccomp for all\nlibc-linked binaries (TLS blocker, see trap mode status below). Lazy shadow:\nmemfd creation deferred to mmap time (not at open).\n\n| Syscall | native | kbox (auto) | overhead |\n|---------|--------|-------------|----------|\n| stat | 2.2us | 18.0us | 8.2x |\n| open+close | 2.9us | 25.5us | 8.8x |\n| lseek+read | 1.0us | 24.0us | 24.0x |\n| write | 1.1us | 24.5us | 22.3x |\n| getpid | 0.3us | 10.8us | 36.0x |\n\nopen+close improved 2.5x vs previous baseline (63us -> 25.5us) due to lazy\nshadow creation: the shadow memfd is only materialized when the guest actually\ncalls mmap, not on every open. Most files are never mmapped; the benchmark\nopens and immediately closes without mmap, so zero shadow overhead.\n\nSeccomp notification round-trip (getpid baseline): ~10.8us. Lower than\nprevious 12.5us measurement due to node load variance; the structural\nfloor is ~10-13us depending on kernel/CPU cache state.\n\nRewrite analysis (--syscall-mode=rewrite --forward-verbose, diagnostic only):\n- bench-test (static musl): 1 exec-segment, 154 candidates\n- /bin/echo (dynamic, Alpine busybox): 0 exec candidates + 549 in\n  ld-musl-x86_64.so.1 = 549 total\n- Analysis reads ELF header+phdrs first (capped at REWRITE_PHDR_MAX =\n  256KB), then reads each executable segment individually (capped at\n  REWRITE_ANALYZE_MAX = 16MB cumulative). Never mallocs the full binary.\n\nOverhead decomposition (lazy shadow):\n- stat (18.0us): ~11us notif + ~7us for process_vm_readv (path) + LKL\n  fstatat + ABI conversion (128B -> 144B) + process_vm_writev (stat buf).\n- open+close (25.5us): two notifs (~21us) + ~4.5us for path translation +\n  LKL openat + FD table insert + LKL close + FD table remove.\n  No shadow creation -- lazy shadow defers to mmap. Previously 63us when\n  shadow was created eagerly at open time (memfd_create + fstat + pread +\n  ftruncate + write + lseek + ADDFD = ~38us eliminated).\n- lseek+read (24.0us): two notifs. Back-to-back notifications in tight\n  loop benefit from hot kernel caches. Each LKL call is trivial (lseek\n  resets pointer, read copies 64B in one chunk).\n- write (24.5us): ~11us notif + ~13us for process_vm_readv (64B buf) +\n  LKL write + optional TTY mirror.\n- getpid (10.8us): pure seccomp round-trip, returns hardcoded PID 1.\n\nOverhead decomposition: seccomp notification vs LKL execution\n(derived from lazy shadow measurements, notif floor = 10.8us):\n\n| Syscall | kbox | notif cost | LKL+copy | notif share |\n|---------|------|-----------|----------|-------------|\n| stat | 18.0us | 10.8us (1x) | 7.2us | 60% |\n| open+close | 25.5us | 21.6us (2x) | 3.9us | 85% |\n| lseek+read | 24.0us | 21.6us (2x) | 2.4us | 90% |\n| write | 24.5us | 10.8us (1x) | 13.7us | 44% |\n| getpid | 10.8us | 10.8us (1x) | ~0us | 100% |\n\nWith lazy shadow, open+close is now notification-dominated (85%) rather\nthan shadow-creation-dominated. The seccomp round-trip is the bottleneck\nfor all syscalls except write (44%, dominated by LKL + process_vm_readv).",
            "old_string": "## Performance Baseline (x86_64, 10K iterations, Alpine ext4)\n\nMeasured 2026-03-22, release build (`BUILD=release`), `tests/guest/bench-test`\non node1 (x86-64). Median of 5 runs each. Native = bare metal (no kbox).\nBuild includes `src/rewrite.c` with `--syscall-mode` support; auto mode skips\nELF analysis (no per-syscall overhead vs default seccomp).\n\n| Syscall | native | kbox (seccomp) | kbox (auto) | overhead |\n|---------|--------|---------------|-------------|----------|\n| stat | 2.2us | 18.5us | 17.7us | 8.4x |\n| open+close | 2.9us | 63.0us | 63.2us | 21.7x |\n| lseek+read | 1.0us | 25.7us | 27.0us | 25.7x |\n| write | 1.1us | 27.1us | 26.9us | 24.6x |\n| getpid | 0.2us | 12.5us | 13.8us | 62.5x |\n\nSeccomp and auto columns are within noise -- auto mode introduces zero\nper-syscall overhead (falls back to seccomp immediately, no ELF scan).\n\nSeccomp notification round-trip (getpid baseline): ~12.5us. This is the\nirreducible floor for any USER_NOTIF-dispatched syscall.\n\nRewrite analysis (--syscall-mode=rewrite --forward-verbose, diagnostic only):\n- bench-test (static musl): 1 exec-segment, 154 candidates\n- /bin/ls (dynamic, Alpine busybox): 0 exec candidates + 549 in\n  ld-musl-x86_64.so.1 = 549 total\n- Analysis reads ELF header+phdrs first (capped at REWRITE_PHDR_MAX =\n  256KB), then reads each executable segment individually (capped at\n  REWRITE_ANALYZE_MAX = 16MB cumulative). Never mallocs the full binary.\n- Byte-pattern scan (over-counts on x86-64); actual rewriting will use\n  instruction-boundary-aware decoder (see P5 step 3 phases)\n\nOverhead decomposition:\n- stat (18.5us): 12.5us notif + ~6us for process_vm_readv (path) + LKL\n  fstatat + ABI conversion (128B -> 144B) + process_vm_writev (stat buf).\n  3 kernel transitions total.\n- open+close (63.0us): two notifs (25us) + ~38us for path translation +\n  LKL openat + shadow memfd creation (fstat + pread + memfd_create +\n  ftruncate + write + ADDFD ioctl) + LKL close. Shadow creation dominates.\n- lseek+read (25.7us): two notifs. Baseline predicts 25us (2x12.5),\n  but back-to-back notifications in a tight loop run faster than\n  standalone getpid due to hot kernel caches (seccomp filter, notif\n  path). Each call is a single LKL call; read copies 64B in one chunk.\n- write (27.1us): 12.5us notif + ~15us for process_vm_readv (64B buf) +\n  LKL write + optional TTY mirror. Single chunk (64B << 128KB).\n- getpid (12.5us): pure seccomp round-trip, returns hardcoded PID 1.\n\n~4.5 host context switches per intercepted syscall (weighted average).\n\nOverhead decomposition: seccomp notification vs LKL execution\n(measured on node1, median of 10 runs, seccomp notification floor =\n12.6us from getpid):\n\n| Syscall | kbox | notif cost | LKL+copy | notif share |\n|---------|------|-----------|----------|-------------|\n| stat | 17.6us | 12.6us (1x) | 2.8us | 82% |\n| open+close | 63.3us | 25.2us (2x) | 35.2us | 42% |\n| lseek+read | 26.4us | 25.2us (2x) | 0.2us | 99% |\n| write | 26.4us | 12.6us (1x) | 12.7us | 50% |\n| getpid | 12.6us | 12.6us (1x) | ~0us | 100% |\n\nThe seccomp notification round-trip dominates most syscalls: 82-100%\nfor stat, lseek+read, and getpid. Exceptions are open+close (58%\nLKL+shadow creation) and write (50% LKL + process_vm_readv copy).\nlseek+read is almost entirely notification overhead -- back-to-back\nnotifs in a tight loop hit hot kernel caches, so actual LKL work\n(lseek is a pointer reset, read copies 64B) is negligible.",
