ated\nnotification overhead.\n\nTier 2 estimates: replace 3.6us signal overhead with ~0.04us hook call.\nRequires binary rewriting + trampoline. Un-rewritten syscalls fall\nto Tier 1 (RET_TRAP), not Tier 3 (USER_NOTIF).\n\n### Improvement ratios (getpid baseline)\n\n| Transition | Speedup | What changes |\n|------------|---------|-------------|\n| seccomp -> Tier 1 | 3.0x | USER_NOTIF (10.8us) -> SIGSYS (3.6us), eliminate process_vm |\n| Tier 1 -> Tier 2 | ~90x | SIGSYS (3.6us) -> call *%rax hook (~0.04us) |\n| seccomp -> Tier 2 | ~270x | Full notification elimination |\n\nObservations:\n- open+close with lazy shadow is notification-dominated (85% notif).\n  Tier 1 eliminates ~15us of notification overhead, projecting ~11us.\n  A shadow cache for repeated opens of the same file would cut further.\n- write cost (13.7us LKL+copy) includes ~1-2us of process_vm_readv\n  which Tier 1/2 eliminate. Projected ~14us in Tier 1.\n- lseek+read: two SIGSYS deliveries (~7.2us) + LKL work (~2.4us) =\n  ~10us. 2.4x improvement over seccomp.\n- Tier 1 has zero execve overhead (no binary re-translation needed).\n  Tier 2's ~5ms re-translation cost per exec is a concern for\n  shell-heavy workloads but does not affect Tier 1.\n- The 3.6us trap overhead has room for optimization: the current\n  dispatch path is shared with seccomp mode and not tuned for\n  in-process use. A fast-path for simple syscalls (getpid, brk)\n  could reduce this to ~2us.\n\nCaveats:\n- Tier 1 getpid is the only real measurement. stat/open/write/lseek\n  projections use the measured 3.6us signal cost as the notification\n  component; LKL costs are from the seccomp decomposition above.\n  Full Tier 1 benchmarks require resolving the arch_prctl TLS blocker",
